1998-08-17  Preston Brown  <pbrown@xanadu>

    * src/versit/.cvsignore, src/.cvsignore: ignore .inslog2 insure++
    log files.

    * src/todoview.h.bak, src/todoview.cpp.bak: removed old backup files.

    * src/versit/.cvsignore, src/.cvsignore: ignore temporary insure files
    (.ix*)

    * src/versit/vobject.c, src/topwidget.cpp, src/todoview.h,
    src/todoview.cpp, src/kdated.cpp, src/eventwinrecur.h,
    src/eventwingeneral.h, src/eventwindetails.h, src/editeventwin.cpp:
    found out what was causing leaks to be reported in initMetaObject
    in some of my classes.  It happens when there is no signal in the
    class which emits a pointer !! (why?)  I forwarded on my findings
    to the trolls for analysis.  Maybe a bug in insure++, but I doubt it.

    I put back the old todo editor, and it still needs lots of work,
    but no leaks.  Leaks also fixed in the various windows of the
    event editor, and also some obscure but nasty leaks in vobject.c.
    Various other minor things as well.

1998-08-12  Preston Brown  <pbrown@xanadu>

    * src/topwidget.cpp: started adding signal/slot connection for
    editing events.

    * src/todoview.h.bak, src/todoview.cpp.bak: added the old versions
    in so that I can refer to them if I need details of the old
    implementation.

    * src/todoview.h, src/todoview.cpp, src/baselistview.cpp: I couldn't
    fix the bugs in the todolist, I just kept getting those crazy errors
    from insure that there was some leaking going on in the constructor.
    The weird thing is, even when I made an EMPTY class which looked like
    todoview, but did absolutely NOTHING (not even in the constructor,
    besides basic inheritance and a single signal/slot connection)
    I still got the message that there was a leak in initMetaObject.

    I copied baselistview over todoview and started hacking, as for
    some reason (even though it ALSO inherits from KTabListBox and has
    signals/slots) it doesn't trigger this message that there is a leak.
    I don't know if there was a leak or not, but TodoView was crufty
    and broken enough that a fresh start was warranted anyway.  We can
    display todos but not much else at this point.

1998-08-05  Preston Brown  <pbrown@xanadu>

    * src/todoview.cpp, src/main.cpp, src/listview.cpp,
    src/ksmalldaydisp.h, src/ksmalldaydisp.cpp, src/kmonthview.h,
    src/kmonthview.cpp, src/kagenda.cpp, src/calobject.h,
    src/calobject.cpp, src/calendarlatexprinter.cpp: changed a bunch of
    return/parameter values to use references instead of static objects.
    Still lots of memory leaks I don't know how to fix.  Maybe someone
    wishes to assist?  Yeah, right.  Things are a bit broken right now,
    don't expect things to be hunkey-dorey.

1998-08-04  Preston Brown  <pbrown@xanadu>

    * src/topwidget.cpp, src/todoview.h, src/todoview.cpp, src/kdpevent.h,
    src/kdpevent.cpp, src/alarmdaemon.cpp, src/.psrc: made most methods
    in kdpevent return const & (that should have previously), and made
    parameters passed by reference as well.  More cleanups in calobject
    to follow.  Hopefully we can squash these memory problems.

    * src/versit/vcc.y, src/versit/vcc.c, src/topwidget.cpp,
    src/todoview.cpp, src/editeventwin.cpp, src/calobject.h,
    src/calobject.cpp, src/alarmdaemon.h, src/alarmdaemon.cpp: I
    seem to have fixed the mem leaks in the alarm daemon.  I changed
    the alarmSignal method to be a reference instead of an explicitly
    created pointer.  I am not really understanding how this fixed the
    .moc memory leak stuff, but it is cleaner anyway, and my reading of
    "Effective C++" is teaching me a bunch of stuff that I didn't know
    about C++ when I started this project.  More code cleanups to follow.

